    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Oblong, laterally compressed, fairly plain dark-grey fish with small scales, a continuous dorsal fin and a mask-like black patch around eyes. Head somewhat pointed and teeth fused to form a parrot-like beak. Juveniles quite different in colour, being yellow with a black vertical bar though eye, another in front of tail and a black patch around base of pectoral fin.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3596",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 90 cm total length and a mass of 7 kg.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3597",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to southern KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3598",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Juveniles sometimes found under floating objects at sea and have been seen cleaning other fish. Adults on inshore reefs from depths of about 5â€“100 m, often found in crevices and caves.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3599",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Generalist feeder, consuming a wide range of sedentary or slow-moving benthic invertebrates including sponges, tunicates, barnacles, bryozoans, sea urchins and holothurians, as well as some algae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3600",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches sexual maturity at a length of about 40 cm and an age of about 5.7 years. Has a protracted breeding season with a peak in spring. Grows fairly slowly and has a longevity of about 14 years.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3601",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly unmistakable and the only species in this family found in the Western Cape. A second darker species, the Natal knifejaw <i>O.&nbsp;robinsoni</i>, occurs from about Algoa Bay eastwards.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3602",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
